<subSubSection id="E45EB0E1AC7B63706CF5624D1A63D2C1" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="6416820A29176BE6FCD9023146ACA497" pageNumber="53">
The genus 
<taxonomicName id="F02CEC7E3FEF82414B38A49F55751D59" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Hemigrammus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hemigrammus Gill, 1858</taxonomicName>
is one of the most diverse in the Characidae, presently with 45 species recognized as valid and widely distributed in Neotropical cis-andean river basins (Lima et al., 2003; Bertaco &amp; Carvalho, 2005, Zarske et al. 2006). Currently allocated as incertae sedis in Characidae (see Lima et al., 2003), 
<taxonomicName id="CB393D652A418B65CD6FE72E04651086" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Hemigrammus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hemigrammus</taxonomicName>
has not been investigated since the monograph of 
<normalizedToken id="37343D0AC936ECC67F609D60F7E1B483" originalValue="Géry">Gery</normalizedToken>
(1977). 
<normalizedToken id="2F80CA32A696E6AEC89DC42C2F835EBD" originalValue="Géry">Gery</normalizedToken>
, based on the extensive revision of the genus presented by Marion Durbin Ellis in Eigenmann (1918), defined 
<taxonomicName id="F4803325CC52538051B6B5C3D7F4CF42" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Hemigrammus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hemigrammus</taxonomicName>
by the presence of premaxillary teeth in two rows, inner row with five or more teeth, scale sheath covering the caudal-fin lobes, and an incomplete lateral line. According to Bertaco &amp; Carvalho (2005), the notable anatomical diversity within 
<taxonomicName id="F5CD2165CFDFF0E3F6891283770FD0C9" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Hemigrammus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hemigrammus</taxonomicName>
and the high number of species recognized are likely to be the major reasons behind the lack of phylogenetic analyses of its species, as well as of the genus among characids. Examination of several lots from Museo de Ciencias Naturales de Guanare, Venezuela, revealed a new and sexually dimorphic species of 
<taxonomicName id="E7F82D24AE6997E942BA1426AF5C3234" class="Actinopterygii" family="Characidae" genus="Hemigrammus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Characiformes" pageNumber="53" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">Hemigrammus</taxonomicName>
, which is described herein.
</paragraph>
